stence: From Heresy to Orthodoxy -- t16. Global Power Relationships in the Seventies: The View from the Kremlin -- tPART SIX. Some Reflections -- t17. Soviet Politics: From the Future to the Past? -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tRUSSIAN RESEARCH CENTER STUDIES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Dynamics of Soviet Politics is the result of reflective and thorough research into the centers of a system whose inner debates are not open to public discussion and review, a system which tolerates no public opposition parties, no prying congressional committees, and no investigative journalists to ferret out secrets. The expert authors offer an inside view of the workings of this closed system a view rarely found elsewhere in discussions of Soviet affairs. Their work, building as it does on the achievements of Soviet studies over the last thirty years, is firmly rooted in established knowledge and covers sufficient new ground to enable future studies of Soviet politics and social practices to move ahead unencumbered by stereotypes, sensationalism, or mystification. Among the subjects included are: attitudes toward leadership and a general discussion of the uses of political history; the dramatic cycles of officially permitted dissent; the legitimacy of leadership within a system that has no constitutional provision for succession; the gradual adoption of Western-inspired administrative procedures and "systems management"; a study of group competition, and bureaucratic bargaining; Khrushchev's virgin-lands experiment and its subsequent retrenchment; the apolitical values of adolescents; the problems of integrating Central Asia into the Soviet system; a history of peaceful coexistence and its current importance in Soviet foreign policy priorities, and, finally, an overview of Soviet government as an extension of prerevolutionary oligarchy, with an emphasis on adaptation to political change.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aPolitical science. 0aPolitik. 0aPolitisches System. 0aPouvoir (Sciences sociales). 0aPower (Social sciences). 4aHISTORY / General. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General. 4aPolitical science -- Decision making. 4aSoviet Union -- Politics and government -- 1953-1985. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBRZEZINSKI, ZBIGNIEW, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCARLISLE, DONALD S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCOCKS, PAUL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCocks, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDANIELS, ROBERT V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDONALDSON, ROBERT H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Robert V., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHODGSON, JOHN H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHOUGH, JERRY F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeer, Nancy Whittier, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMARANTZ, PAUL, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMASSELL, GREGORY J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMILLER, ROBERT F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMILLS, RICHARD M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMOULY, RUTH W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRAKOWSKAHARMSTONE, TERESA, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSPECHLER, DINA, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aULAM, ADAM B., ec